Q1. What is the hierarchy of the InputStream and OutputStream classes?
-->InputStream and OutputStream are the two root abstract classes in Java's byte stream hierarchy. They are part of the java.io package and 
    are used to read and write binary data (such as images, audio, videos, PDFs, etc.).
    
    InputStream → Used to read bytes from a source.
    OutputStream → Used to write bytes to a destination.
    
    Since they are abstract classes, we cannot create their objects directly. Instead, we use their subclasses.

    Hierarchy of InputStream:
    -------------------------
                        Object
                       │
                InputStream (abstract)
                       │
 ┌─────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────┐
 │                     │                             │
FileInputStream   ByteArrayInputStream      PipedInputStream
 │
BufferedInputStream
 │
DataInputStream
 │
ObjectInputStream


    Important subclasses
    --------------------
    FileInputStream → Reads data from a file.
    BufferedInputStream → Improves reading performance using a buffer.
    DataInputStream → Reads primitive data types (int, double, boolean, etc.).
    ObjectInputStream → Reads serialized Java objects.
    ByteArrayInputStream → Reads data from a byte array.
    PipedInputStream → Reads data sent from another thread.



    Hierarchy of OutputStream
    -------------------------
                        Object
                       │
               OutputStream (abstract)
                       │
 ┌─────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────┐
 │                     │                             │
FileOutputStream  ByteArrayOutputStream     PipedOutputStream
 │
BufferedOutputStream
 │
DataOutputStream
 │
ObjectOutputStream
 │
PrintStream


Important subclasses
FileOutputStream → Writes data to a file.
BufferedOutputStream → Improves writing performance using a buffer.
DataOutputStream → Writes primitive data types.
ObjectOutputStream → Writes serialized Java objects.
PrintStream → Prints formatted data (e.g., System.out).


Interview Points (Very Important)
---------------------------------
InputStream and OutputStream belong to the java.io package.
They are abstract classes.
They work with byte streams (8-bit data).
Used for binary files like images, PDFs, audio, videos, etc.
InputStream is for reading data.
OutputStream is for writing data.
They provide common methods like:
read()
write()
close()
flush() (only in OutputStream)


Example:
--------
import java.io.FileInputStream;
import java.io.FileOutputStream;
import java.io.InputStream;
import java.io.OutputStream;

public class ReadAndWriteFile{
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        try{
            InputStream in = new FileInputStream("data.txt");
            OutputStream outV = new FileOutputStream("vowels.txt");
            OutputStream outC = new FileOutputStream("consonents.txt");
            OutputStream outD = new FileOutputStream("digits.txt");
            OutputStream outS = new FileOutputStream("special.txt");

            int data;
            while((data = in.read()) != -1){
                // char ch = (char) data;
                if((char)data == 'A' || (char)data == 'E' || (char)data == 'I'|| (char)data == 'O'|| (char)data == 'U' || (char)data == 'a' || (char)data == 'e' || (char)data == 'i'|| (char)data == 'o'|| (char)data == 'u' ){
                    outV.write((char)data);

                }else  if(Character.isDigit((char)data)){
                    outD.write((char)data);

                }else  if(  !Character.isDigit((char)data)  && !Character.isLetter((char)data) && !Character.isWhitespace((char)data)){
                    outS.write((char)data);

                }else{
                    outC.write((char)data);
                }
            }


        }catch(Exception e){
            e.printStackTrace();

        }


    }
}





